WEBVTT

00:08.860 --> 00:12.800
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.480 --> 00:33.820
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.440 --> 00:38.140
And here are your hosts.

00:42.520 --> 00:44.440
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane.

00:44.680 --> 00:47.940
Harry Harrison has made a name for himself in science fiction in many areas.

00:48.320 --> 00:51.860
He's noted for his novels, short stories, and the anthologies he's edited.

00:52.300 --> 00:55.740
One of Harrison's notable contributions is the popularization of so-called adventure

00:55.740 --> 00:56.480
science fiction.

00:56.680 --> 01:01.020
It's typified by the trilogy whose volumes are aptly named Death World One, Death World

01:01.020 --> 01:02.300
Two, and Death World Three.

01:02.740 --> 01:06.320
Harrison told us how this particular brand of science fiction originated with the writing

01:06.320 --> 01:07.380
of Death World One.

01:07.980 --> 01:10.760
You mentioned the fact that there's adventure science fiction.

01:11.200 --> 01:17.180
Well, don't laugh, but at that time in science fiction, which was Campbell, which was analog.

01:17.700 --> 01:22.900
If you were a true blue reader, you read Starling's stories in Sling Wonder, because you'd

01:22.900 --> 01:25.700
had to wait another three weeks for the next issue of astounding.

01:25.860 --> 01:26.640
That's where the action was.

01:27.180 --> 01:28.720
And he had been very cerebral.

01:28.940 --> 01:31.440
He had a whole novel of people talking to each other.

01:31.900 --> 01:33.880
Nothing moving at all, no action.

01:34.600 --> 01:37.880
And I want to do a book that had action part of the plot.

01:38.240 --> 01:41.020
I mean, that's sort of stupid to say now with all the guns blowing heads away.

01:41.160 --> 01:46.000
I mean, that whole gore school and the whole sword and sorcery, sword and butchery.

01:46.300 --> 01:48.800
I mean, action galore for no reason at all.

01:49.940 --> 01:52.360
But in those days, it was getting dim, I thought.

01:52.980 --> 01:56.200
So I worked out, but I didn't want to do an action plot for action, say.

01:56.840 --> 02:00.940
So I'm a great back plotter, and I find a reason to do a book, and then I put a book

02:00.940 --> 02:01.460
to the reason.

02:02.040 --> 02:04.060
And the reason I wanted to have the action, I wanted to have a realistic.

02:04.600 --> 02:05.420
So I thought it was Superman.

02:08.360 --> 02:12.720
And in this book, you find, if you look at it closely, it's done two or three levels.

02:12.820 --> 02:14.000
The action plots a service.

02:14.520 --> 02:18.600
But there below that is the idea of Superman, the Nietzsche talked about.

02:19.280 --> 02:21.100
And that Superman magazine talks about.

02:21.520 --> 02:24.040
And I'm very much against Superman, physical Superman.

02:24.560 --> 02:27.660
And if you look in the book, you'll see that if you are so brutalized to be

02:27.660 --> 02:30.860
physically a Superman, your intellectual content is zero.

02:31.500 --> 02:32.920
And I said it in a number of different ways.

02:33.820 --> 02:37.360
And I'm very much against militarism, and that's been there in a number of different ways.

02:37.840 --> 02:39.660
All of it couched in his venture plot.

02:40.080 --> 02:43.060
And it's up to the reader to read it whichever way he wants.

02:44.700 --> 02:47.800
And he'll find a good adventure plot if he wants to find even more about it.

02:48.060 --> 02:51.480
Remember when I first published it, a reader in England came up to me, and

02:51.480 --> 02:54.740
I was looking forward to great return from literate Englishmen about

02:55.840 --> 02:57.700
heavily intellectual content.

02:58.360 --> 03:02.280
And he said, all areas that I read that book, I sold my friends to read,

03:02.380 --> 03:07.360
all I like it, you did, but you tell me, all read, I said, it's all about guns.

03:18.260 --> 03:20.860
The protagonist of Death World One is Jason DenAlt.

03:21.180 --> 03:23.760
Harrison liked him so much that he had to write two more installments.

03:24.520 --> 03:27.280
The Death World two and three came out by happenstance.

03:27.760 --> 03:29.620
It's just that the character was successful.

03:30.260 --> 03:32.680
I want to write another adventure style book.

03:33.480 --> 03:36.200
And I realized after I wrote it, I left the ending open.

03:36.660 --> 03:39.720
You had to get these people off that planet, the certain part of them had to leave.

03:40.120 --> 03:41.100
They just go for killing things.

03:41.520 --> 03:43.800
He starts thinking about it and their friends with his.

03:44.360 --> 03:46.100
And he's a weak man personally.

03:46.580 --> 03:48.860
And he has, like I say, he supplies a part.

03:48.960 --> 03:51.560
So they don't supply, they have the big bodies and the tiny point heads.

03:52.120 --> 03:54.900
He's a weakling in their terms, but he's a man of intelligence.

03:55.660 --> 03:57.940
So therefore, I said, gee, what if there was another planet?

03:58.020 --> 03:58.600
He had a problem.

03:59.020 --> 04:00.380
He'd have to go along and organize it.

04:00.600 --> 04:02.060
And then the plot developed.

04:02.940 --> 04:06.360
I did that once more, and that was the end of it, as far as I was concerned.

04:06.920 --> 04:07.900
People asked for another Death World.

04:08.000 --> 04:12.180
And no, I run that particular plot device while I was pinned into it.

04:12.500 --> 04:13.400
It worked three times.

04:13.440 --> 04:14.200
It worked pretty well.

04:14.700 --> 04:17.720
Harrison told us his books usually have philosophical content.

04:18.300 --> 04:19.500
Death World Two, for instance.

04:20.380 --> 04:26.040
OK, Death World Two, you may think it's about going off and blowing things up

04:26.040 --> 04:27.640
and killing things and rushing around.

04:28.220 --> 04:29.020
It really is.

04:29.100 --> 04:33.660
The entire book is about the difference in meaning between ethics and ethos.

04:34.240 --> 04:35.340
And that's what it's about.

04:36.100 --> 04:37.880
I keep repeating over and over through that thing.

04:38.240 --> 04:39.340
And a lot of guns go off.

04:39.440 --> 04:40.260
A lot of good things happen.

04:40.420 --> 04:41.400
You learn a bit of Esperanto.

04:42.100 --> 04:47.060
But also, what science fiction can do, it's a book that takes the study

04:47.060 --> 04:49.480
of a philosophical question or a problem of meaning.

04:50.260 --> 04:52.420
We'll have more with Harry Harrison on our next show.

