07:04.820 --> 07:08.240
One of Science Fiction writer Harry Harrison's most unforgettable character is the slippery

07:08.240 --> 07:10.140
Jim DeGrees, the stainless steel rat.

07:10.500 --> 07:13.500
The Stainless Steel Rats adventure spin five novels so far.

07:13.800 --> 07:16.860
We asked Harrison where he got the concept of a stainless steel rat.

07:17.560 --> 07:18.880
I remember the basic idea.

07:19.480 --> 07:25.480
It was just that, as the old rat says, we have flesh and blood rats and wooden buildings.

07:25.480 --> 07:27.740
We'll have stainless steel rats and concrete ones.

07:28.480 --> 07:32.120
Then Harrison went on to tell us a bit about the first novel in the series, the Stainless

07:32.120 --> 07:33.960
Steel Rat, and how the idea then grew.

07:34.900 --> 07:40.300
It's basically a very old idea of the villain as hero.

07:41.280 --> 07:42.420
Turn the world on his head.

07:42.520 --> 07:43.560
This is what we have in the saint.

07:44.480 --> 07:46.420
Who tended to pontificate a little bit too much.

07:47.260 --> 07:52.840
It's Rupert of Hentzau and that prisoner of Zenda.

07:54.440 --> 07:57.280
We all love him better than we do the goodie goodies with his job.

07:57.840 --> 08:02.340
It is, if you pardon the expression, my dear friend Kingsley Amis had a pick-a-rest novel.

08:02.980 --> 08:04.500
Don't be ashamed if you don't understand what that means.

08:04.720 --> 08:05.780
I said, thanks Kingsley.

08:05.840 --> 08:06.560
I ran off to a dictionary.

08:07.340 --> 08:08.700
The pick-a-rest novel is just that.

08:08.880 --> 08:11.160
The villain as the hero as villain and villain as hero.

08:12.200 --> 08:16.960
And when I realized what I was doing, I had come onto a formula and I was trying to get

08:16.960 --> 08:17.980
humor into it as well.

08:18.160 --> 08:19.280
There was no humor in Science Fiction.

08:19.280 --> 08:20.240
There was nothing that I was doing.

08:20.320 --> 08:24.260
Anyone else alive, the character developed as he went along.

08:25.160 --> 08:27.700
And I get clues back from readers about it.

08:28.120 --> 08:35.120
And an English reader told me he likes to read this thing because the hero does all the

08:35.120 --> 08:38.100
thing he wish he could do against society and gets away with it.

08:38.280 --> 08:39.620
Everyone hates bureaucracy.

08:40.480 --> 08:41.980
And I said, my God, you're right.

08:42.040 --> 08:44.340
I thought about it in the very next rat book.

08:45.120 --> 08:46.720
The first chapter, nothing to do with the rest of the book.

08:46.720 --> 08:50.060
The first chapter we look at, just something happens to his dear wife, Angelina, and the

08:50.060 --> 08:50.740
enemy has her.

08:50.780 --> 08:51.220
And he goes off.

08:51.520 --> 08:54.140
The enemy is the internal review service, the old IRS man.

08:54.500 --> 08:58.220
He goes and burns on all income tax records for the whole planet, cheering everybody up.

08:58.460 --> 08:59.620
And the story begins.

09:00.220 --> 09:03.140
But that's something we all wish could happen tomorrow except that people work for the IRS.

09:04.080 --> 09:07.200
The Stainless Steel Rat novels form a humorous adventure series.

09:07.600 --> 09:10.140
We ask Harris in what place humor has in Science Fiction.

09:10.740 --> 09:11.460
Very little.

09:12.640 --> 09:13.960
It could have a bigger one.

09:14.540 --> 09:16.220
And the answer is a very mechanical one.

09:17.240 --> 09:19.400
Editors, for the most part, are dummies.

09:20.640 --> 09:25.180
And even the few bright ones have their own particular taste in humor.

09:25.520 --> 09:26.560
That is a matter of taste.

09:27.220 --> 09:31.020
You bring an adventure novel in, and it will say, yeah, well, Harry's unbetter, but it

09:31.020 --> 09:33.020
moves along, people are killed, I'll buy it.

09:33.620 --> 09:37.340
Bring a love story in, oh, well, girl gets kissed, you know, it's a little boring, but I'll buy it.

09:37.740 --> 09:40.100
You bring in a humor novel, he doesn't laugh.

09:40.100 --> 09:42.040
He does not buy it.

09:43.120 --> 09:46.940
And if they laugh, I've heard them say, one of them is a rejecter, it was too funny.

09:47.600 --> 09:49.260
They're afraid the readers won't laugh.

09:49.900 --> 09:52.260
So the only way you can have a reputation is a humor writer.

09:53.080 --> 09:54.220
And how do you get a humor writer?

09:54.300 --> 09:55.720
You've got to sell a book, but you can't sell it.

09:55.960 --> 09:57.220
It's a catch-22 thing.

09:57.520 --> 09:59.500
And I snuck it in the Stainless Steel Rat.

09:59.700 --> 10:04.300
I would make each one a little bit funny than the one before, and eventually, the editor was laughing, readers were laughing,

10:04.460 --> 10:05.760
hurrah, I'm a humor writer.

10:06.700 --> 10:10.700
Harrison's early characters, Jason DenAult and Slippery Jim DeGrees, are strong characters.

10:11.180 --> 10:14.500
But Harrison told us science fiction is really based on ideas, not characters.

10:15.360 --> 10:18.100
Science fiction is not a character-based form of fiction.

10:18.500 --> 10:23.180
You can have three-dimensional characters in science fiction, but the idea comes first.

10:23.360 --> 10:24.300
It's not an idea fiction.

10:25.080 --> 10:27.640
The form of fiction, we can have an idea as a hero.

10:27.840 --> 10:29.980
The main thing that has that is what you call three-dimensional.

10:31.820 --> 10:34.980
Have the idea for a character who would do these things.

10:36.980 --> 10:43.960
Which means far too often in science fiction, you'll get two-dimensional characters who just act the assigned role of the plot, given to by the author.

10:44.580 --> 10:45.840
And we don't mind reading that.

10:45.940 --> 10:52.840
We really want to read about the action to make good science fiction, viable, interesting, fun science fiction,

10:53.320 --> 10:57.580
when you have to assign the character to the role, you must build his character as a character.

10:58.080 --> 10:59.700
That's where the art comes in.

10:59.760 --> 11:01.200
There are two things in all kinds of fiction.

11:01.340 --> 11:03.560
The craft of science fiction, constructing your plot.

11:04.080 --> 11:06.780
The art of science fiction is making your characters three-dimensional.

11:08.200 --> 11:09.740
Which is true for any character I write.

11:11.160 --> 11:15.080
Very rarely in science fiction do you have character-based fiction.

11:15.160 --> 11:16.340
If you have, it's usually not science fiction.

