24:43.660 --> 24:47.340
Harry Harrison's grim novel of an overpopulated near future New York

24:47.340 --> 24:49.560
was the basis for the movie Soilent Green.

24:50.120 --> 24:52.380
This movie made its appearance in the early 1970s,

24:52.420 --> 24:54.420
and it starred Charlton Heston and Edward G. Robinson.

24:54.880 --> 24:59.360
One of the movie's claims to fame is that it was the last motion picture Edward G. Robinson played in.

24:59.920 --> 25:02.700
We spoke with Harrison about the transformation of the novel to the movie,

25:03.080 --> 25:06.540
and we were particularly interested how the movie came to be plotted around cannibalism,

25:06.680 --> 25:08.140
whereas this was never mentioned in the novel.

25:08.140 --> 25:13.000
Harrison told us an interesting story which vividly shows how things apparently work in Hollywood.

25:13.880 --> 25:18.460
The first time I heard about the fact that they wanted to make a film out of this book

25:18.460 --> 25:21.160
was when I approached for a contract and I signed it,

25:21.520 --> 25:25.120
and then it turned out the firm that bought it was a front for MGM,

25:25.760 --> 25:27.220
and they sold MGM for one dollar.

25:27.600 --> 25:29.340
They hate to pay the writer a decent fee,

25:29.420 --> 25:30.800
but for some reason they pay everyone else.

25:30.880 --> 25:32.160
They don't like to pay writers in Hollywood.

25:32.160 --> 25:40.100
And it turned out that the producer Walter Zeltzer and lead actor Chuck Heston

25:40.100 --> 25:42.440
have been trying to sell MGM for five years,

25:43.020 --> 25:47.700
and they couldn't sell MGM for that overpopulation wasn't important enough to a film on.

25:48.200 --> 25:52.320
So they then got a moronic screenwriter who put in cannibalism.

25:52.440 --> 25:55.400
He thought they'd eat that up in MGM, and they did.

25:55.600 --> 25:57.180
They thought it'd be a great idea for a film.

25:57.380 --> 25:59.180
It was bought as a cannibalism film.

26:00.220 --> 26:03.020
And I saw the screenplay and it was pretty atrocious,

26:03.240 --> 26:04.200
and I could not do anything.

26:04.340 --> 26:06.480
By contract I couldn't change one word.

26:07.060 --> 26:10.080
So what I did do, I kept saying on memos what was wrong physically,

26:10.340 --> 26:12.620
how it could not work, and they made a lot of changes.

26:12.760 --> 26:15.760
I went down the set and pointed out things that hadn't been done,

26:16.200 --> 26:19.240
and I gave copies of the book to all the actors and all the technical people,

26:19.300 --> 26:20.160
and they got very interested.

26:20.940 --> 26:22.380
And I talked to Eddie Robinson.

26:24.500 --> 26:27.260
I remember he talked to Dick Fleischer.

26:27.260 --> 26:30.540
I heard him say, I don't understand who I'm supposed to be, what is this role?

26:31.280 --> 26:33.700
And there's no way of talking that rotten screenplay what it was.

26:34.180 --> 26:36.180
So I asked if I could talk to him.

26:36.220 --> 26:38.360
I introduced myself, and we had lunch.

26:38.820 --> 26:39.460
I said, I wrote the book.

26:39.620 --> 26:40.280
Oh, that's very interesting.

26:40.440 --> 26:41.940
The Literate Man, the art collector, you know?

26:42.460 --> 26:50.400
I explained that in the book in the year 2000, that is me, my army record, my age.

26:51.420 --> 26:56.360
The hero there, not here, the old man is the only person who knew the good world as it was playing.

26:56.360 --> 26:58.840
He said, the only person who lived when the world was green.

26:59.260 --> 27:00.300
He said, that's a good idea.

27:00.520 --> 27:00.980
It's not bad.

27:01.560 --> 27:04.780
Having got that much, he went away and acted.

27:05.280 --> 27:06.860
A lot of that was created on camera,

27:07.720 --> 27:09.920
the interface between the director and the actors.

27:10.420 --> 27:12.460
And I like to think myself, that was there all the time.

27:12.920 --> 27:15.100
And I like to feel, A, it was my book,

27:15.580 --> 27:18.320
and B, if there was some worth in the film, I helped to add to it.

27:35.760 --> 27:41.100
One of the lead characters, the old man Saul, played by Robinson, is actually Harrison in 1999, as he mentioned.

27:41.500 --> 27:42.100
Here he explains.

27:43.020 --> 27:46.060
To keep him in the three-dimensional character, I guess, I use myself when I'll be of that age.

27:46.360 --> 27:47.460
I don't want to live in that world.

27:47.620 --> 27:48.320
That's why I wrote the book.

27:48.460 --> 27:50.340
I do not want to be that person at that time.

28:05.440 --> 28:09.500
Although the plot of make room, make room was significantly altered in Soylent Green,

28:09.980 --> 28:12.740
Harrison told us that on the whole, he is pleased with the movie.

28:13.260 --> 28:16.420
The technical people were so tremendous, and the acting was so good.

28:17.180 --> 28:21.680
And it does what science fiction does so well, background as foreground.

28:22.220 --> 28:26.280
You go to see it, it's a stupid little detective plot, and you know it's going to be Bonnie's maid in Soylent Green.

28:26.880 --> 28:30.760
And then about a week later, you start thinking about that horrible world, that green world you're living in.

28:31.000 --> 28:31.680
My God!

28:32.080 --> 28:33.260
And it succeeds in that play.

28:33.400 --> 28:35.680
It was sort of a shocker, an emotional shocker.

28:36.760 --> 28:37.000
It works.

28:37.080 --> 28:38.320
I think it works pretty well as a film.

28:38.640 --> 28:39.440
There have been no complaints.

28:40.040 --> 28:41.940
It's the only film MGM made money on that year.

28:42.380 --> 28:46.740
That was the year the Great Walls bombed, it cost $14 million, and grossed $500,000.

28:47.500 --> 28:50.340
So MGM should be happy, and Reston should be happy.

28:50.340 --> 28:51.180
I can't complain.

